defaultNick Molhodefault: To answer your question at the 
defaultUK
default level, which I hope will be helpful, in 2011 renewables provided 10% of 
defaultUK
default power, on average. On the projections going forward, a wide range of reports such as the offshore valuation report that was done by Government and industry and the work that Pöyry did for the Committee on Climate Change suggest that renewables could provide 60% or more of 
defaultUK
default electricity demand by 2030. Clearly, there is potential beyond that for the percentage to increase, although a clear challenge for the UK is the importance of increasing its interconnection links with the rest of Europe. In order to maximise its renewable electricity potential, the 
defaultUK
default needs to have export routes to 
defaultEurope
default to enable it to share some of the excess power at times of lower demand. That would bring economic benefits with it. That is why we have been calling for the UK Government, alongside their energy policy, to have a strategic interconnection strategy with their European 
defaultpartners, to make sure that we can guarantee system security and maximise export opportunities in a way that is as beneficial as possible to our economy.
defaultQ85 default&#xa0; 
